\f2\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 1. Describe the initialization method used, including assimilation of data, spin-up, or any other method.\'a0\'a0\
The initial condition is obtained by data assimilation of present-day observations. \
Original data input was modified to create "a close to 1995 state\'94:\
	Initial data set are modified to "match more 1995".\
	-present-day ice thickness/surface by BedMachine Antarctica v3 ( Morlighem, 2022)\
	-subtracted the equivalent of 20 years of observed ice thinning rate :\
	-Grounded ice from Schroeder et al. (2019)\
	-Floating shelf B. Smith et al (2020)\
	-Added Thwaites shelf back using Bedmap2 dataset (Fretwell et  al 2013)\
	-For Amundsen sector slower Velocities 1996 (Rignot et al ,2014)\
	Modified netcdf: Extras/BedMachineAntarcticav3_plusSECschroeder1992_plusSmithfloat.nc\
\
Adjoint inversion using ISSM's gradient-based optimization (M1QN3).  Two\
sequential inversions are performed:\
  (a) InversionB \'97 invert for ice rheology B (Paterson law), targeting observed\
      surface velocities with a combination of velocity misfit and\
      regularization cost functions.\
  (b) InversionFriction1 \'97 invert for the basal friction coefficient C\
      (Budd law, p=q=1), again targeting observed surface velocities.\
A second-pass inversion (Inversion2B) refines B after the friction coefficient.\
\
The cost function minimizes the  misfit between modeled and observed surface velocities.\
It includes both absolute and logarithmic misfits (Morlighem et al., 2010) as well as a2\
regularization term. The weights assigned to each node in the cost function vary based\
on current thinning rates (B. Smith et al., 2020) and height above flotation, such that\
areas currently experiencing high thinning rates have higher weights in the relative mis\
fit term and areas with a large height above flotation have a higher weight in the absolute \
misfit term. To perform this thermal model simulation, we extrude the 2D mesh \
to a 3D mesh, project the SSA velocities onto this 3D mesh surface and resolve thermal equation\
 assuming steady-state conditions \
 Based on the resulting three-dimensional temperature and velocity fields, viscosity and basal \
friction coefficients are iteratively updated three times following the procedure described\
 in Dawson et al. (2022). We then collapse the three-dimensional fields\
back into a two-dimensional ice-sheet representation governed by the SSA equations\
Then a 20-year free-surface relaxation brings the geometry toward a dynamically consistent state (with observed BMB field , and RACMO SMB Clim).\
With this relaxed output ,  BMB parameter tuning after the tuning protocol was done.\
A final one-year (1995) transient run under e.g. CESM2-WACCM historical forcing  with tuned K produces the\
CESM-specific 1995 starting state used for all CESM2-WACCM experiments.\
Then a history matching specific to the forcing scenario was done, such that the historic run until 2020 matches the mass load trends like in Otosaka. \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

